338":"1240–1338","–Female":"Deceased","about 1290":"about 1290","1253":"1253","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1370":"1370","1270":"1270","1292":"1292","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1338":"1338","1321":"1321","1287":"1287","before 1291":"before 1291","about 1287":"about 1287","before 1270":"before 1270","about 1285":"about 1285","Broxton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Broxton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Nantwich, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Nantwich, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Charlton, England":"Haughton, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bird","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a young or a small and slender person, from Middle English <i>brid</i>, <i>bird</i>, <i>burd</i> (Old English <i>bird</i>, <i>brid</i>, perhaps also <i>byrd</i>) ‘bird, young bird’, also ‘young man, young woman, child’.","Irish: Anglicized form of a number of Irish names erroneously thought to contain the element <i>éan</i> ‘bird’, in particular <i>Ó hÉinigh</i> (see   Heagney  ), <i>Ó hÉanna</i> (see   Heaney  ), <i>Ó hÉanacháin</i> (see   Heneghan  ), and <i>Mac an Déaghanaigh</i> (see   McEneaney  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘bird’, as for example German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Vogel  , French   Loiseau  , Czech <b>Ptáček</b> (see   Ptacek  ) and <b>Pták</b>, Polish   Ptak  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kingbird","meanings":["Native American (Chippewa; also <b>King Bird</b>): translation into English of the Chippewa personal name <i>Ogimaa-bines(i)</i>, meaning literally ‘the bird that is king’ and referring to the mythological bird-like creature thunderbird. See also   Bird   4.","History: The progenitor of the large family of the Kingbirds from the Red Lake, MN, was Ogimaa-bines, a musical gifted Chippewa spiritual leader."]},{"name":"Byrd","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Bird  ."]},{"name":"Heaney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Aidan, Malachy, Nuala, Ronan.","Irish:","Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hÉanna</b> and <b>Ó hÉinne</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Éanna</i>’, a very common personal name of uncertain meaning. It was borne by various early Christian saints, most notably Saint Éanna of Aran. The name has been erroneously understood as containing the element <i>éan</i> ‘bird’ and as a result the surname was sometimes Anglicized as   Bird  ."]},{"name":"Blackbird","meanings":["Native American (also <b>Black Bird</b>): translation into English of a personal name such as Lakota Sioux <i>Ziŋtkala Sapa</i>, which is composed of <i>ziŋtkala</i> ‘bird’ and <i>sapa</i> ‘black’. See also   Bird   4.","English (Durham): nickname for someone with a dark beard, from Middle English <i>blak</i> ‘black’ + <i>berd</i> ‘beard’ (Old English <i>blæc</i> + <i>beard</i>)."]},{"name":"Burd","meanings":["English: variant of   Bird  .","Jewish (from Poland and Ukraine): nickname for a man with a notable beard, from a southern Yiddish pronunciation of Yiddish <i>bord</i> ‘beard’."]},{"name":"Burt","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Bird  ,   Bright  , or   Burd  .","German: Middle High German <i>burt</i> ‘that which is due or proper’, therefore a nickname for someone who has fulfilled his obligations properly.","Jewish (from Poland and Ukraine): variant of   Burd  ."]},{"name":"Hummingbird","meanings":["Native American (Cherokee): translation into English of a personal name based on the Cherokee name <i>walela</i> for a hummingbird. See also   Bird   4."]},{"name":"Heagney","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hÉignigh</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Éigneach</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘forceful’. The spelling of the Irish name was often simplified to <b>Ó hÉinigh</b> and then Anglicized as   Heaney   or ‘translated’ as   Bird  , the latter because of a perceived similarity to <i>éan</i> ‘bird’."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]},{"name":"le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Profit’ or ‘sharp’.","2  ♀, ♂ ‘Upright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"David le Bird was born in 1270, in Broxton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 5 sons with Mabel de Broxton. He died in 1291, at the age of 21."},"et":{"1270–1291":"1270–1291","1253–1321":"1253–1321","1285–Male":"1285–Surnud","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1290–1370":"1290–1370","1291–Male":"1291–Surnud","1292–Male":"1292–Surnud","1240–1338":"1240–1338","–Female":"Surnud","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1253":"1253","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1370":"1370","1270":"1270","1292":"1292","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1338":"1338","1321":"1321","1287":"1287","before 1291":"enne 1291","about 1287":"umbes 1287","before 1270":"enne 1270","about 1285":"umbes 1285","Broxton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Broxton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Nantwich, Cheshire, England